# Lesson 3-5 — Shapes of Graphs

Source: (Module 3, Lesson 3-5, Int1_0305_practice.docx)

## Today's Goals

* Identify line symmetry in the graph of a function and explain its meaning.
* Determine the intervals where a function is increasing, decreasing, or constant.
* Locate relative maxima and minima on a graph and interpret them in context.
* Describe the end behavior of a function using limit notation.

## Vocabulary

* **Line symmetry** — A graph has line symmetry if it can be reflected across a vertical line (often the [ y ]-axis) and map onto itself.
* **Increasing** — A function is increasing on an interval if, as [ x ] increases, [ f(x) ] also increases (the graph rises from left to right).
* **Decreasing** — A function is decreasing on an interval if, as [ x ] increases, [ f(x) ] decreases (the graph falls from left to right).
* **Relative maximum** — A point on the graph where the function changes from increasing to decreasing, forming a "peak."
* **Relative minimum** — A point on the graph where the function changes from decreasing to increasing, forming a "valley."
* **End behavior** — The direction the graph tends as [ x ] approaches [ +\infty ] or [ -\infty ].

## Learn: Symmetry of Graphs

A function's graph may be symmetric with respect to a vertical line. The most common type is symmetry about the [ y ]-axis, where [ f(-x) = f(x) ] for all [ x ] in the domain. When a graph has this symmetry, the left side mirrors the right side.

### Key Concept: Identifying Symmetry

* Visually inspect whether the left and right halves of the graph are mirror images across a vertical line.
* If the graph is symmetric about [ x = 0 ], then [ f(-a) = f(a) ] for any value [ a ].
* Explain your conclusion by naming the line of symmetry or stating that no line symmetry exists.

## Example 1 — Determine Line Symmetry

Examine each graph and decide whether it has line symmetry. If it does, state the line of symmetry and explain why.

### Step 1: Visually Inspect the Graph

Look at the left and right sides of the curve relative to a vertical line (often the [ y ]-axis).

### Step 2: State and Justify Your Conclusion

For a graph symmetric about the [ y ]-axis:
[
f(-x) = f(x)
]

If no mirror image exists across any vertical line, state that there is no line symmetry.

> **Review Note:** Problems 1–4 each show a distinct graph. Students must inspect the image and explain their reasoning. See Review Notes for image descriptions.

## Example 2 — Interpret Symmetry in Context

Apply symmetry concepts to real-world scenarios modeled by graphs.

### Step 1: Read the Scenario and Identify the Graph's Features

Understand what the variables represent (e.g., width vs. area, horizontal distance vs. height).

### Step 2: Find and Interpret the Symmetry

Determine whether the graph has a line of symmetry. If so, describe what that symmetry means in the situation.

For a sprinkler spraying water symmetrically:
[
\text{The path is symmetric about the vertical line through the maximum height.}
]
This means the water lands the same distance to the left and right of the center line.

## Learn: Increasing and Decreasing Intervals

A function can be described as increasing, decreasing, or constant over specific intervals of [ x ]. These intervals are read from left to right along the [ x ]-axis.

### Key Concept: Reading Direction

* **Increasing:** The graph rises as you move from left to right.
* **Decreasing:** The graph falls as you move from left to right.
* State intervals using open interval notation (or inequalities) based on the [ x ]-values.

## Example 3 — Determine Where [ f(x) ] Is Increasing and/or Decreasing

For each graphed function, identify the [ x ]-intervals where the function is increasing and where it is decreasing.

### Step 1: Trace the Graph Left to Right

Starting at the leftmost point, observe whether the [ y ]-values are going up or down.

### Step 2: Record the Intervals

Write the intervals using [ x ]-values. For example:
[
\text{Increasing on } (-\infty, 0); \quad \text{Decreasing on } (0, \infty)
]

> **Review Note:** Problems 7–10 each show a distinct graph. Students trace each curve left-to-right to classify intervals. See Review Notes for image descriptions.

## Learn: Extrema of a Function

Extrema are the high and low points on a graph. A **relative maximum** is a point higher than all nearby points; a **relative minimum** is lower than all nearby points.

### Key Concept: Identifying Extrema

* A relative maximum occurs where the function changes from increasing to decreasing.
* A relative minimum occurs where the function changes from decreasing to increasing.
* Read the coordinates [ (x, y) ] of each extremum from the graph.

## Example 4 — Determine Extrema

For each graphed function, locate all relative maxima and relative minima. State the coordinates of each point.

### Step 1: Locate Turning Points

Find the "peaks" (relative maxima) and "valleys" (relative minima) on the graph.

### Step 2: Identify and Label Each Point

State the coordinates and classify each. For example:
[
\text{Relative maximum at } (-1, 4)
]
[
\text{Relative minimum at } (2, -3)
]

> **Review Note:** Problems 11–14 each show a distinct graph with varying numbers of turning points. See Review Notes for image descriptions.

## Example 5 — Interpret Extrema in Context

Use the concept of extrema to analyze real-world graphs and explain what each point means in the given situation.

### Step 1: Locate the Given Point on the Graph

Identify the coordinates of the marked point (e.g., point [ A ] on a golf-ball-height graph).

### Step 2: Classify the Point

Decide whether the point is a relative maximum, relative minimum, or neither by examining the behavior of the graph around it.

### Step 3: Describe the Meaning in Context

Explain what the value represents. For a golf ball height graph:
[
\text{Relative maximum at point } A \text{ means the ball reaches its highest height at that distance from the tee.}
]

For a rollercoaster height graph, each labeled point ([ B ], [ C ], [ D ], [ F ]) is classified and interpreted similarly.

## Learn: End Behavior

End behavior describes what happens to [ f(x) ] as [ x ] becomes very large in the positive or negative direction.

### Key Concept: Describing End Behavior

* As [ x \to +\infty ], observe whether [ f(x) \to +\infty ], [ f(x) \to -\infty ], or [ f(x) \to k ] (some constant).
* As [ x \to -\infty ], observe the same.
* Write the end behavior using arrow notation or limit-style statements.

## Examples 6 and 7 — Determine End Behavior

For each graphed function, describe the end behavior as [ x ] approaches [ +\infty ] and as [ x ] approaches [ -\infty ].

### Step 1: Examine the Right Side of the Graph

As [ x ] gets larger (moves to the right), determine whether the graph rises or falls.
[
x \to +\infty
]

### Step 2: Examine the Left Side of the Graph

As [ x ] gets smaller (moves to the left), determine whether the graph rises or falls.
[
x \to -\infty
]

### Step 3: Summarize

Write the complete end behavior. For example:
[
\text{As } x \to +\infty, \; f(x) \to +\infty
]
[
\text{As } x \to -\infty, \; f(x) \to -\infty
]

> **Review Note:** Problems 17–20 each show a distinct graph. Students observe both tails to describe end behavior. See Review Notes for image descriptions.

## Mixed Exercises

These exercises combine all skills from the lesson: line symmetry, increasing/decreasing intervals, extrema (relative maxima and minima), and end behavior.

For problems 21–22, analyze a single graph and provide a complete description: state whether it has line symmetry, identify all intervals of increase and decrease, locate and classify all extrema, and describe the end behavior.

Problems 23–24 present real-world contexts (a rock thrown into the air; computers affected by a virus) and ask students to apply the appropriate graphical analysis skill.

Problem 25 is a "Which One Doesn't Belong?" activity: students evaluate four statements about a single graph and determine which statement is false, then justify their conclusion using evidence from the graph.

